SIMPLE: eclipse
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Eclipse
<hw>E*clipse"</hw> <pr>(⟦esl⟧*kl⟦icr⟧ps")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>⟦eacute⟧clipse</ets>, L. <ets>eclipsis</ets>, fr. Gr.
<grk>'e`kleipsis</grk>, prop., a forsaking, failing, fr.
<grk>'eklei`pein</grk> to leave out, forsake; <grk>'ek</grk> out +
<grk>lei`pein</grk> to leave. See <er>Ex-</er>, and
<er>Loan</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <def>An
interception or obscuration of the light of the sun, moon, or other
luminous body, by the intervention of some other body, either between it
and the eye, or between the luminous body and that illuminated by it. A
lunar eclipse is caused by the moon passing through the earth's shadow;
a solar eclipse, by the moon coming between the sun and the observer. A
satellite is eclipsed by entering the shadow of its primary. The
obscuration of a planet or star by the moon or a planet, though of the
nature of an eclipse, is called an <stype>occultation</stype>. The
eclipse of a small portion of the sun by Mercury or Venus is called a
<stype>transit</stype> of the planet.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ In ancient times, eclipses were, and among unenlightened
people they still are, superstitiously regarded as forerunners of evil
fortune, a sentiment of which occasional use is made in
literature.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>That fatal and perfidious bark,⟦br⟧
Built in the <qex>eclipse</qex>, and rigged with curses dark.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The loss, usually temporary or partial, of light,
brilliancy, luster, honor, consciousness, etc.; obscuration; gloom;
darkness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>All the posterity of our fist parents suffered a perpetual
<qex>eclipse</qex> of spiritual life.</q> <rj><qau>Sir W.
Raleigh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>As in the soft and sweet <qex>eclipse</qex>,⟦br⟧
When soul meets soul on lovers' lips.</q>
<rj><qau>Shelley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Annular eclipse</b></col>. <fld>(Astron.)</fld> <cd>See
under <er>Annular</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Cycle of eclipses</b></col>.
<cd>See under <er>Cycle</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eclipse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Eclipse
<hw>E*clipse"</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Eclipsed</conjf> <pr>(⟦esl⟧*kl⟦icr⟧pst")</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Eclipsing</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To cause
the obscuration of; to darken or hide; -- said of a heavenly body;
<as>as, the moon <ex>eclipses</ex> the sun</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To obscure, darken, or extinguish the beauty,
luster, honor, etc., of; to sully; to cloud; to throw into the shade by
surpassing.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧His <xex>eclipsed</xex> state.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>My joy of liberty is half <qex>eclipsed</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Eclipse</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Eclipse
<hw>E*clipse"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To suffer an
eclipse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>While the laboring moon⟦br⟧
<qex>Eclipses</qex> at their charms.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>eclipsis</ent>⟦br⟧
